alogue etc.) should be on the needy/vulnerable people. \ufffd Place importance on evidence\u2010based action. \ufffd Put human development centre stage so that when addressing climate change, human issues would automatically be approached. Other recommendations \ufffd Regional vulnerability index cannot avoid gaps since official statistics tend to focus on national level, not community level. \ufffd There is a need for additional indicators, e.g., health access as it is not universal; individuals and households/districts may be better representation of realities on the ground. 24 \ufffd Explore the carbon footprint concept. \ufffd Establishment of regional banks for climate action but who will capitalize them? \ufffd Adopt a future, vision\u2010oriented approach. Is there a new economic paradigm? \ufffd Consider a new technological direction (take examples from Thailand, Malaysia, China). \ufffd In many countries, it not a norm as yet to include environment education into school syllabus. India is a good example of this. 25 COUNTRY EXPERIENCES (Afghanistan, Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, Iran, Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan, Sri Lanka) Afghanistan ISSUES BARRIERS \ufffd Intensifying and varying climate cycles, temperatures and precipitation \ufffd Droughts and severe storms \ufffd Adverse impact on agricultural productivity \ufffd Lack of financial and technical resources \ufffd Lack of institutional capacity Bangladesh ISSUES BARRIERS \ufffd Food insecurity is a key concern \u2010 75% of population is susceptible to severe impact \ufffd Cyclones, droughts and excessive rains hamper human development progress \ufffd Increasing cases of malaria and dengue threaten people\u2019s health \ufffd Existential problems associated with CC \ufffd Lack of capacity of existing system/structure \ufffd Lack of transparency in government \ufffd CC is not integrated into national development plans Bhutan ISSUES BARRIERS \ufffd Tragedy of the commons (communities come to share a common pool of resources) is a reality \ufffd Food and water insecurity \ufffd Root causes are not well tackled in current policy efforts to address CC India ISSUES BARRIERS \ufffd Geographical vastness implies diversity of issues, namely, poverty and ecological \ufffd Lack of information and finance for alternative technology \ufffd Lack of institutional capacity \ufffd Poor mangrove/wetland management, affecting coastal communities \ufffd Attitudinal factors impede public action on CC Iran ISSUES BARRIERS \ufffd High population growth \u2013 youth oriented; threatens to increase the level \ufffd Economic growth focused policies, thus the low priority for CC 26 of unsustainable energy use \ufffd Rapid urbanization \ufffd Non green energy intensive economy \ufffd CC sensitive sector such as agriculture dominates share in GDP and employment \ufffd Changes in rainfall and drought patterns \ufffd \ufffd Mitigation and adaptation are not on policy agenda and national development plans. Hence, adaptation measures are not in place to compensate loss of income and welfare \ufffd Pressure from rapid growth for energy demand forces the government to focus more on meeting energy needs of domestic market \ufffd Lack of capability to drive a low carbon economy and to absorb and transfer efficient technology \ufffd Uncertainty in climate prediction; mixed periodic climate variability and climate changes.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "a0bf1925-33a3-48ba-9238-aa785766513f": {"__data__": {"id_": "a0bf1925-33a3-48ba-9238-aa785766513f", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/asia-pacific-human-development-report-climate-change-asia-stakeholders-consultation-report", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "exclu