_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "a6e4c472-bab4-4909-96aa-62542c5c06c5": {"__data__": {"id_": "a6e4c472-bab4-4909-96aa-62542c5c06c5", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/asia-pacific-human-development-report-climate-change-pacific-stakeholders-consultation-report", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Asia-Pacific Human Development Report on Climate Change: Pacific Stakeholders Consultation Report", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/asia-pacific-human-development-report-climate-change-pacific-stakeholders-consultation-report", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "c5c5c496411610bdb6fb64719c76bfabad1b671577e253dcf2db195a6736b5bb"}, "3": {"node_id": "8e8ccb39-5cdc-4af2-a269-858fb3ae4300", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/asia-pacific-human-development-report-climate-change-pacific-stakeholders-consultation-report", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "660d93df5b19ef84a973213001689e2533808b3dbb829f6454fab54e16efaf01"}}, "hash": "4e95a7e2dae3e1418e356a705817c4a787f9a77284903964b6b38b2fcd881096", "text": "1 has not mentioned the type of organisation (Table 1). \uf0b7 Among the participants, 59.3 per cent were satisfied about the consultation, 25.9 per cent were very satisfied and 14.8 per cent were somewhat satisfied. (Table 2, Figure 2) Those 44 who were somewhat satisfied about the consultation suggested in advance notification about the consultation would satisfactorily improve the quality of the event. Figure 2: Level of satisfaction in the consultation 14.8% 59.3% 25.9% Not at all satisfied Somewhat satisfied Satisfied Very satisfied \uf0b7 Over 88% of participants reported that discussions and presentations were informative or very informative where as the rest (11.1%) said that they were somewhat informative. Over 92% of the participants stated that the discussions and presentations were participatory or very participatory while the rest (7.4%) reported that they were somewhat participatory as the allocated time was not enough (Table 3a and table 3b). \uf0b7 Above 88 percent of the participants were able or very able to get their views across in the group. 7.4% of participants had no opinion on this and all of them are government representatives. \uf0b7 People at the centre: Vulnerabilities and opportunities in the Pacific came out as the most important issue related to CC. 50.9 percent responses endorsed this issue. The second highest responses were for Mapping and measuring human development from a climate change perspective in the pacific and 39.6 percent responses towards that point. Few participants also voted for Making the low carbon society a reality: going beyond the adaptation-mitigation dichotomy (5.7 per cent) and for a vision of Human Development through a low carbon society (3.8 percent) (Table 5). \uf0b7 29.1% of responses favored in providing case studies for the RHDR. 25.5% responses favored in participating in network discussions, 20% would preferred to share their experience, 12.7% responses preferred in research contribution and another 12.7% percent responses favored in contributing to advocacy (Table 6). 45 Suggestions for improvement: \uf0b7 Even though the 25.9 percent of participants have reported that the consultation does not have to have any change, all the others have mentioned that some parts of the consultation have to be improved. 22.2% of participants said that the time should be the component that has to be improved. 14.8% of participants said that the material and presentations have to be further improved. 11.1% of participants would like if the participation is further improved. 7.4% of participants prefer if the communication is improved more (Table 8). Table 1: Number of participants from different agencies Agencies No of participants Percent UN 03 11.1 NGO/CSO 06 22.2 Government 11 40.7 Media 1 3.7 INGO 1 3.7 Universities 3 11.1 Regional organizations 1 3.7 No Answer 1 3.7 Total 27 100 Table 2: Level of satisfaction in the consultation Level of satisfaction No of participants Percent Not at all satisfied 0 0.0 Somewhat satisfied 4 14.8 Satisfied 16 59.3 Very satisfied 7 25.9 Total 27 100 Table 3a: Opinion on quality of presentations and discussions: Whether they are informative Discussions and presentations Number of participants Percent 46 Very informative 13 48.1 Informative 11 40.7 Somewhat informative 3 11.1 Not at all informative 0 0.0 No opinion 0 0.0 Total 27 100.0 Table 3b: Opinion on quality of presentations and discussions: Participatory Discussions and presentations Number of participants Percent Very participatory 17 63.0 Participatory 8 29.6 Somewhat participatory 2 7.4 Not at all participatory 0 0.0 No opinion 0 0.0 Total 27 100.0 Table 4: Did you get your views across in the group discussion?", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "8e8ccb39-5cdc-4af2-a269-858fb3ae4300": {"__data__": {"id_": "8e8ccb39-5cdc-4af2-a269-858fb3ae4300", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/asia-pacific-human-development-report-climate-change-pacific-stakeholders-consultation-report", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Asia-